jsdom provides `requestAnimationFrame`. The original test was passing before my changes. Let me compare what changed.

Before my change, the render effect was:
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const tick = (): void => {
    render();
    if (transportState === "playing") {
      rafRef.current = requestAnimationFrame(tick);
    }
  };
  rafRef.current = requestAnimationFrame(tick);
  return (): void => { cancelAnimationFrame(rafRef.current); };
}, [render, transportState]);
```

After my change, when not playing (which is the test case), the new code does:
```tsx
const tick = (): void => {
  if (transportState === "playing") {
    // ... SAB read + renderArrangement ...
    rafRef.current = requestAnimationFrame(tick);
  } else {
    render();
  }
};
rafRef.current = requestAnimationFrame(tick);
```

This should be equivalent - when stopped, it calls `render()` once and doesn't re-schedule. But the dependencies array changed significantly. Maybe the issue is with the new dependency list causing infinite re-renders.

Actually wait - I think the issue is that the render effect now depends on `sabCursorRef` which is a React ref. Refs don't trigger re-renders but they are new on every render... No, `useTransportCursor` returns a `RefObject` which is stable.

Let me check if the issue is simply that I have the test hanging from before. Let me make sure all processes are dead first, then test with the original test only:

