Still looping. The `clipPeaks` state update is the culprit. The `fetchPeaks` effect runs, resolves (since clips is empty), calls `setClipPeaks({})`. This triggers a re-render. The re-render causes the "Re-render on state changes" effect to fire (because `clipPeaks` changed reference). This calls `renderOnce()` again. The jsdom's "Not implemented" message fires each time.

But the actual problem is that `setClipPeaks({})` creates a new reference each time, causing the component to re-render, but since `clips` is stable (`{}`), the fetchPeaks effect should NOT re-run. The dependency `[clips, pool, engine.ctx.sampleRate]` only changes when `clips` changes. Since `clips` stays `{}` after the store state is set, it shouldn't re-run.

So the loop is: render -> effects run -> fetchPeaks fires (async) -> setClipPeaks({}) -> re-render -> effects run. At this point, clipPeaks changed, but clips/pool/sampleRate didn't, so fetchPeaks effect doesn't re-run. But the "Re-render on state changes" effect re-runs, calling renderOnce() once more (the "Not implemented" message). That's 3 messages total per test.

Actually looking at the output, there are many "Not implemented" messages (20+), suggesting the loop continues. The issue might be that `pool` (from `useMediaPool()` mock) returns a new object each render, causing the fetchPeaks effect to re-run endlessly.

Let me check the `useMediaPool` mock:

```tsx
vi.mock("@audio/media-pool/use-media-pool", () => ({
  useMediaPool: () => ({
    getPeaks: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue(undefined),
  }),
}));
```

Each call to `useMediaPool()` returns a NEW object `{ getPeaks: vi.fn()... }`. This means `pool` changes every render, which makes the `fetchPeaks` effect re-run every render, which calls `setClipPeaks({})` every time, which causes a new render. This is an infinite loop.

The fix: make the mock return a stable object.

